ata table\",\"viewFullscreen\":\"View in full screen\",\"weekdays\":[\"Sunday\",\"Monday\",\"Tuesday\",\"Wednesday\",\"Thursday\",\"Friday\",\"Saturday\"]}},\"type\":\"chart\",\"fonts\":\"Graphik\",\"debug\":false},\"evals\":[\"hc_opts.tooltip.formatter\",\"hc_opts.legend.labelFormatter\"],\"jsHooks\":[]}</script>\n</div>\n<br/>\n</div>\n```\n:::\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"body-section\">\n<br/>\n<div id=\"big-section-title\">How is Parole Release Eligibility Determined?</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"regular-text\">In Idaho, a felon is anyone sentenced to a crime punishable by death or imprisonment in the state prison. Idaho felons must be sentenced by a judge to a minimum term of incarceration with no parole eligibility. The judge may then impose an additional indeterminate sentence, during which inmates may be released on parole. These two portions of the sentence, often called a “unified sentence” may not exceed the statutory maximum set for  the crime. Correctional employees make a sentencing calculation when an inmate is committed to the Department of Correction. Based on this information, the Commission conducts a review to determine the initial parole hearing date, which is set at most six months before an inmate’s first parole eligibility (i.e., six months before the minimum term expires). All inmates who are eligible for parole release must be considered at least once by the Commission.</div>\n<br/>\n<br/>\n</div>\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"body-section\">\n<br/>\n<div id=\"big-section-title\">People who are Eligible for Parole</div>\n<br/>\n</div>\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n::: {.panel-tabset}\n### Race\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"body-section\">\n<br/>\n<div id=\"regular-text\"></div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"visualization\">No Data</div>\n<br/>\n</div>\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n\n### Gender\n\n### Age\n:::\n\n\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n